stylometry: When looking at an output from @RISK, I can see how much the data varies (mean, minimum, maximum, standard deviation) in different situations. @RISK can show me how the data will behave when different factors in the situation change. When making a decision about how many calandars to order I will be looking for how much money I will make or lose from not meeting or exceeding demand. I will also see how profitable it will be to send the calandars back to the manufacturer. In the @RISK simulation I will be looking at the different maximum potential demands in relationship to the standard deviation. The situation with the highest minimum and maximum and lowest standard deviation would be the ideal choice because this demonstrates that this would be most profitable with the least amount of risk.
